{{mergeto|Personification}}

A '''prosopopoeia''' is a rhetorical device in which an absent or non-existant person is said to be saying or doing something. The term derives from the [[Greek language|Greek]] roots meaning a face, a person, to make.

Examples:
*"If [[Miller Huggins]] was alive today, he'd be turning over in his grave". -[[Yogi Berra]], speaking of a former [[New York Yankees|Yankees]] manager.
*"The [[Devil]] made me do it."
*Often a prosecutor will suggest to [[jury|jurors]] that a [[homicide]] victim is "speaking to us through the evidence".

